Note:
GEOHASH - Hierarchical string-encoded spatial hashes

Provides three hierarchical spatial hashes used widely in GIS and search
infrastructure:

  GeoHash  (Niemeyer 2008) - Base-32 interleaved bit hash. The string
           prefix preserves spatial locality: nearby points share a long
           prefix. Used by ElasticSearch, Redis GEO commands, and many
           map tile schemes.
  S2 Cell  (Google) - Hierarchical quad-tree projection of the sphere onto
           six face cubes. The cell IDs are 64-bit integers and the cells
           are roughly equal area. Used by Google Maps, Foursquare, and
           Pokemon Go.
  H3 Cell  (Uber) - Hierarchical hexagonal grid. Aperture 7 hexagons at
           each level. The hexagonal shape gives more uniform neighbor
           relationships than quad cells. Used by Uber, Lyft, and many
           ride-share / dispatch systems.

This file implements the Niemeyer-2008 GeoHash in full, the S2 Cell ID
construction (level 0-30), and a simplified H3 cell index (cells at the
icosahedron face level, suitable for ~ continent-scale partitioning;
the full H3 grid involves a non-trivial gnomonic projection and is
handled in a future h3_cell.runa).

CITATIONS

  - Niemeyer, G. (2008): "Geohash" specification. geohash.org.
  - Veach, E. (2017): "S2 Geometry library", Google. http://s2geometry.io/
  - Brodsky, I. (2018): "H3: Uber's Hexagonal Hierarchical Spatial Index"
    Uber Engineering Blog. https://eng.uber.com/h3/
  - Sahr, K., White, D., & Kimerling, A. J. (2003): "Geodesic discrete
    global grid systems", Cartography and GIS 30(2), 121-134.

DEPENDENCIES

  - compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/geo_coordinate.runa for GeoCoordinate.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/geo_coordinate.runa" as GeoCoord
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StrCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - GeoHash encoding (Niemeyer 2008)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The GeoHash alphabet is base-32 with the modified-base32 character set
Note: that omits 'a', 'i', 'l', and 'o' (visually ambiguous):
Note:   0123456789bcdefghjkmnpqrstuvwxyz
Note: The encoding bisects the [-180, 180] longitude range and the [-90, 90]
Note: latitude range alternately, building bits from MSB. Each base-32
Note: character encodes 5 bits = 5 bisection steps total (alternating lon/lat).

Process called "geohash_alphabet_char_at" takes idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the ASCII byte value of the geohash base-32 alphabet at
        the given index. Index range [0, 31]. The omitted letters
        (a, i, l, o) leave the alphabet at 32 distinct characters.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Branch ladder. Could be a lookup table but the ladder costs ~ 5
        cycles for the worst case and avoids the data-segment dependency.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 cycles average.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Out-of-range indices return 0 (NUL) so the caller can
        detect corruption.
    @End Security_Scope
    If idx is equal to 0:
        Return 48
    End If
    If idx is equal to 1:
        Return 49
    End If
    If idx is equal to 2:
        Return 50
    End If
    If idx is equal to 3:
        Return 51
    End If
    If idx is equal to 4:
        Return 52
    End If
    If idx is equal to 5:
        Return 53
    End If
    If idx is equal to 6:
        Return 54
    End If
    If idx is equal to 7:
        Return 55
    End If
    If idx is equal to 8:
        Return 56
    End If
    If idx is equal to 9:
        Return 57
    End If
    If idx is equal to 10:
        Return 98
    End If
    If idx is equal to 11:
        Return 99
    End If
    If idx is equal to 12:
        Return 100
    End If
    If idx is equal to 13:
        Return 101
    End If
    If idx is equal to 14:
        Return 102
    End If
    If idx is equal to 15:
        Return 103
    End If
    If idx is equal to 16:
        Return 104
    End If
    If idx is equal to 17:
        Return 106
    End If
    If idx is equal to 18:
        Return 107
    End If
    If idx is equal to 19:
        Return 109
    End If
    If idx is equal to 20:
        Return 110
    End If
    If idx is equal to 21:
        Return 112
    End If
    If idx is equal to 22:
        Return 113
    End If
    If idx is equal to 23:
        Return 114
    End If
    If idx is equal to 24:
        Return 115
    End If
    If idx is equal to 25:
        Return 116
    End If
    If idx is equal to 26:
        Return 117
    End If
    If idx is equal to 27:
        Return 118
    End If
    If idx is equal to 28:
        Return 119
    End If
    If idx is equal to 29:
        Return 120
    End If
    If idx is equal to 30:
        Return 121
    End If
    If idx is equal to 31:
        Return 122
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "geohash_alphabet_index_for_char" takes c as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Inverse of geohash_alphabet_char_at: given an ASCII byte from the
        alphabet, return its index in [0, 31]. Returns -1 for non-alphabet
        characters.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Branch ladder.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 cycles average.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Non-alphabet input returns -1 sentinel.
    @End Security_Scope
    If c is equal to 48:
        Return 0
    End If
    If c is equal to 49:
        Return 1
    End If
    If c is equal to 50:
        Return 2
    End If
    If c is equal to 51:
        Return 3
    End If
    If c is equal to 52:
        Return 4
    End If
    If c is equal to 53:
        Return 5
    End If
    If c is equal to 54:
        Return 6
    End If
    If c is equal to 55:
        Return 7
    End If
    If c is equal to 56:
        Return 8
    End If
    If c is equal to 57:
        Return 9
    End If
    If c is equal to 98:
        Return 10
    End If
    If c is equal to 99:
        Return 11
    End If
    If c is equal to 100:
        Return 12
    End If
    If c is equal to 101:
        Return 13
    End If
    If c is equal to 102:
        Return 14
    End If
    If c is equal to 103:
        Return 15
    End If
    If c is equal to 104:
        Return 16
    End If
    If c is equal to 106:
        Return 17
    End If
    If c is equal to 107:
        Return 18
    End If
    If c is equal to 109:
        Return 19
    End If
    If c is equal to 110:
        Return 20
    End If
    If c is equal to 112:
        Return 21
    End If
    If c is equal to 113:
        Return 22
    End If
    If c is equal to 114:
        Return 23
    End If
    If c is equal to 115:
        Return 24
    End If
    If c is equal to 116:
        Return 25
    End If
    If c is equal to 117:
        Return 26
    End If
    If c is equal to 118:
        Return 27
    End If
    If c is equal to 119:
        Return 28
    End If
    If c is equal to 120:
        Return 29
    End If
    If c is equal to 121:
        Return 30
    End If
    If c is equal to 122:
        Return 31
    End If
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

Process called "geohash_encode" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float, precision as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning:
        Encode the (lat, lon) coordinate into a base-32 geohash string of
        the requested precision. Each character encodes 5 bisection bits,
        alternating between longitude and latitude (longitude first by
        Niemeyer convention).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Maintain mutable [lat_min, lat_max] and [lon_min, lon_max] bins.
        For each output bit:
          - if we are in the longitude phase, bisect [lon_min, lon_max]
            and pick the half containing lon_degrees
          - if we are in the latitude phase, bisect [lat_min, lat_max]
            and pick the half containing lat_degrees
          - shift the accumulator left by 1 and OR in 1 if the upper half
            was chosen
        Every 5 bits, look up the alphabet character and append.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        O(precision) bisections. ~ 30 cycles per character.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Allocates a String for the output. Caller responsible for the
        lifetime of the returned String per the standard Runa String
        management conventions.
    @End Security_Scope
    Note: Allocate output buffer with space for up to `precision` chars + NUL
    Let buffer_size be precision plus 1
    Let buf be allocate(buffer_size)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let lat_min be 0.0 minus 90.0
    Let lat_max be 90.0
    Let lon_min be 0.0 minus 180.0
    Let lon_max be 180.0
    Let phase_lon be 1
    Let bits be 0
    Let bit_count be 0
    Let char_idx be 0
    While char_idx is less than precision:
        Note: Bisect along the current phase
        If phase_lon is equal to 1:
            Let mid be lon_min plus lon_max
            Set mid to mid divided by 2.0
            If lon_degrees is greater than mid or lon_degrees is equal to mid:
                Set bits to bits multiplied by 2
                Set bits to bits plus 1
                Set lon_min to mid
            Otherwise:
                Set bits to bits multiplied by 2
                Set lon_max to mid
            End If
            Set phase_lon to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let mid_lat be lat_min plus lat_max
            Set mid_lat to mid_lat divided by 2.0
            If lat_degrees is greater than mid_lat or lat_degrees is equal to mid_lat:
                Set bits to bits multiplied by 2
                Set bits to bits plus 1
                Set lat_min to mid_lat
            Otherwise:
                Set bits to bits multiplied by 2
                Set lat_max to mid_lat
            End If
            Set phase_lon to 1
        End If
        Set bit_count to bit_count plus 1
        If bit_count is equal to 5:
            Let c be geohash_alphabet_char_at(bits)
            __store_byte(buf, char_idx, c)
            Set bits to 0
            Set bit_count to 0
            Set char_idx to char_idx plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Note: NUL terminate. The raw byte buffer is already a valid C-style
    Note: NUL-terminated string; Runa's String type is just a pointer to such
    Note: bytes, so we can return the buffer pointer directly. The caller owns
    Note: the allocation lifetime; we do NOT deallocate here because the buffer
    Note: IS the returned String.
    __store_byte(buf, char_idx, 0)
    Return buf
End Process

Process called "geohash_decode_lat" takes hash as String returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Decode the latitude (midpoint of the final bin) from the geohash.
        Returns the center of the bin rather than its bounds; callers
        needing the bin extents should also call geohash_decode_lat_error
        and geohash_decode_lon_error.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Mirror the encode algorithm: walk the string character by character,
        invert each to 5 bits, alternately update lat/lon bins. Return
        (lat_min + lat_max) / 2 at the end.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        O(len) bisections. ~ 30 cycles per character.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let lat_min be 0.0 minus 90.0
    Let lat_max be 90.0
    Let lon_min be 0.0 minus 180.0
    Let lon_max be 180.0
    Let phase_lon be 1
    Let n_chars be StrCore.string_length(hash)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n_chars:
        Let c be StrCore.string_char_at(hash, i)
        Let bits_val be geohash_alphabet_index_for_char(c)
        If bits_val is less than 0:
            Set i to n_chars
        Otherwise:
            Let bit_pos be 4
            While bit_pos is greater than 0 or bit_pos is equal to 0:
                Let shifted be bits_val
                Let bit_shift_count be bit_pos
                While bit_shift_count is greater than 0:
                    Set shifted to shifted divided by 2
                    Set bit_shift_count to bit_shift_count minus 1
                End While
                Let bit_set be shifted modulo by 2
                If phase_lon is equal to 1:
                    Let mid_lon be lon_min plus lon_max
                    Set mid_lon to mid_lon divided by 2.0
                    If bit_set is equal to 1:
                        Set lon_min to mid_lon
                    Otherwise:
                        Set lon_max to mid_lon
                    End If
                    Set phase_lon to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Let mid_lat be lat_min plus lat_max
                    Set mid_lat to mid_lat divided by 2.0
                    If bit_set is equal to 1:
                        Set lat_min to mid_lat
                    Otherwise:
                        Set lat_max to mid_lat
                    End If
                    Set phase_lon to 1
                End If
                Set bit_pos to bit_pos minus 1
            End While
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let center_lat be lat_min plus lat_max
    Set center_lat to center_lat divided by 2.0
    Return center_lat
End Process

Process called "geohash_decode_lon" takes hash as String returns Float:
    Let lat_min be 0.0 minus 90.0
    Let lat_max be 90.0
    Let lon_min be 0.0 minus 180.0
    Let lon_max be 180.0
    Let phase_lon be 1
    Let n_chars be StrCore.string_length(hash)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n_chars:
        Let c be StrCore.string_char_at(hash, i)
        Let bits_val be geohash_alphabet_index_for_char(c)
        If bits_val is less than 0:
            Set i to n_chars
        Otherwise:
            Let bit_pos be 4
            While bit_pos is greater than 0 or bit_pos is equal to 0:
                Let shifted be bits_val
                Let bit_shift_count be bit_pos
                While bit_shift_count is greater than 0:
                    Set shifted to shifted divided by 2
                    Set bit_shift_count to bit_shift_count minus 1
                End While
                Let bit_set be shifted modulo by 2
                If phase_lon is equal to 1:
                    Let mid_lon be lon_min plus lon_max
                    Set mid_lon to mid_lon divided by 2.0
                    If bit_set is equal to 1:
                        Set lon_min to mid_lon
                    Otherwise:
                        Set lon_max to mid_lon
                    End If
                    Set phase_lon to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Let mid_lat be lat_min plus lat_max
                    Set mid_lat to mid_lat divided by 2.0
                    If bit_set is equal to 1:
                        Set lat_min to mid_lat
                    Otherwise:
                        Set lat_max to mid_lat
                    End If
                    Set phase_lon to 1
                End If
                Set bit_pos to bit_pos minus 1
            End While
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let center_lon be lon_min plus lon_max
    Set center_lon to center_lon divided by 2.0
    Return center_lon
End Process

Process called "geohash_decode_to_coordinate" takes hash as String returns GeoCoordinate:
    Let result be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set result.latitude_degrees to geohash_decode_lat(hash)
    Set result.longitude_degrees to geohash_decode_lon(hash)
    Set result.altitude_meters to 0.0
    Set result.datum_index to 0
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - S2 Cell ID (Google S2 geometry library)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: S2 partitions the sphere into a quad-tree based on 6 cube faces. Each
Note: cell at level L covers about (pi/(6*4^L)) steradians. Level 30 cells
Note: are roughly 1 cm^2 - finer than any geographic application requires.
Note: The cell ID is a 64-bit integer composed of:
Note:   3 bits  - cube face (0-5)
Note:   2*L bits- quad-tree position bits (Hilbert curve order)
Note:   1 bit   - sentinel bit at position (2L + 1)
Note: This implementation provides cell IDs at levels 0-30. The full S2
Note: includes neighbor lookup, polygon coverage, and other operations
Note: which are out of scope here.

Process called "s2_cell_id_from_lat_lon" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float, level as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute the S2 cell ID at the given level for the given lat/lon.
        Maps lat/lon onto the unit sphere, projects onto the appropriate
        cube face, and computes the quadtree index within that face.
        Returns a 64-bit packed cell ID.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Steps:
          1. Convert lat/lon to (x, y, z) unit vector via the geocentric
             projection.
          2. Determine the cube face: the face whose normal direction is
             the largest |coordinate| with the matching sign.
          3. Compute (u, v) face coordinates as ratios of the other two
             axes to the face axis.
          4. Apply S2's bias function (u, v) -> (s, t) in [0, 1].
          5. Multiply by 2^level and floor to get integer (i, j) in
             [0, 2^level).
          6. Interleave i and j bits in Hilbert-curve order to produce
             the cell index.
          7. Pack face (3 bits) | index | sentinel into a 64-bit ID.
        For brevity the bias function is approximated by the linear
        identity; the proper quadratic form (st = (1 + 3*uv*uv) / 2 if
        uv > 0 else st = (1 - 3*uv*uv) / 2) is omitted because typical
        uses (cell-id-based bucketing) tolerate the small distortion.
        Hilbert ordering is replaced by simple bit-interleaving (Morton
        / Z-order) which gives the same uniqueness property at the
        expense of S2-correct spatial-coherence guarantees.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three trig calls (sin/cos for lat/lon), one branch ladder for
        face selection, ~ 2L bit operations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let pi_over_180 be 0.017453292519943295
    Let phi be lat_degrees multiplied by pi_over_180
    Let lambda be lon_degrees multiplied by pi_over_180
    Note: Unit vector
    Let cos_phi be s2_cos_taylor(phi)
    Let sin_phi be s2_sin_taylor(phi)
    Let cos_lambda be s2_cos_taylor(lambda)
    Let sin_lambda be s2_sin_taylor(lambda)
    Let x_v be cos_phi multiplied by cos_lambda
    Let y_v be cos_phi multiplied by sin_lambda
    Let z_v be sin_phi
    Note: Determine face by largest |axis|
    Let abs_x be x_v
    If abs_x is less than 0.0:
        Set abs_x to 0.0 minus abs_x
    End If
    Let abs_y be y_v
    If abs_y is less than 0.0:
        Set abs_y to 0.0 minus abs_y
    End If
    Let abs_z be z_v
    If abs_z is less than 0.0:
        Set abs_z to 0.0 minus abs_z
    End If
    Let face be 0
    Let u_val be 0.0
    Let v_val be 0.0
    If abs_x is greater than abs_y:
        If abs_x is greater than abs_z:
            If x_v is greater than 0.0:
                Set face to 0
                Set u_val to y_v divided by x_v
                Set v_val to z_v divided by x_v
            Otherwise:
                Set face to 3
                Set u_val to y_v divided by x_v
                Set v_val to z_v divided by x_v
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If z_v is greater than 0.0:
                Set face to 2
                Set u_val to x_v divided by z_v
                Set v_val to y_v divided by z_v
            Otherwise:
                Set face to 5
                Set u_val to x_v divided by z_v
                Set v_val to y_v divided by z_v
            End If
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If abs_y is greater than abs_z:
            If y_v is greater than 0.0:
                Set face to 1
                Set u_val to x_v divided by y_v
                Set v_val to z_v divided by y_v
            Otherwise:
                Set face to 4
                Set u_val to x_v divided by y_v
                Set v_val to z_v divided by y_v
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If z_v is greater than 0.0:
                Set face to 2
                Set u_val to x_v divided by z_v
                Set v_val to y_v divided by z_v
            Otherwise:
                Set face to 5
                Set u_val to x_v divided by z_v
                Set v_val to y_v divided by z_v
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Note: Map (u, v) in [-1, 1] to (s, t) in [0, 1] via linear approximation
    Let s_val be u_val plus 1.0
    Set s_val to s_val divided by 2.0
    Let t_val be v_val plus 1.0
    Set t_val to t_val divided by 2.0
    Note: Convert (s, t) to (i, j) at the requested level
    Let scale_int be 1
    Let level_iter be 0
    While level_iter is less than level:
        Set scale_int to scale_int multiplied by 2
        Set level_iter to level_iter plus 1
    End While
    Let scale_f be 1.0
    Let level_iter2 be 0
    While level_iter2 is less than level:
        Set scale_f to scale_f multiplied by 2.0
        Set level_iter2 to level_iter2 plus 1
    End While
    Let i_f be s_val multiplied by scale_f
    Let j_f be t_val multiplied by scale_f
    Let i_int be 0
    Let j_int be 0
    Note: Stack layout for s2_cell_id_from_lat_lon (stage1 frame, after all
    Note: locals declared above): i_f = rbp-208, j_f = rbp-216, i_int = rbp-224,
    Note: j_int = rbp-232. Verified by inspecting the emitted assembly.
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-208]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-224], rax
    End Assembly
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-216]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-232], rax
    End Assembly
    If i_int is less than 0:
        Set i_int to 0
    End If
    If j_int is less than 0:
        Set j_int to 0
    End If
    If i_int is greater than scale_int minus 1:
        Set i_int to scale_int minus 1
    End If
    If j_int is greater than scale_int minus 1:
        Set j_int to scale_int minus 1
    End If
    Note: Interleave i and j (Morton order) to produce the spatial index
    Let cell_index be 0
    Let bit_idx be 0
    While bit_idx is less than level:
        Let i_bit be i_int
        Let shift_count be bit_idx
        While shift_count is greater than 0:
            Set i_bit to i_bit divided by 2
            Set shift_count to shift_count minus 1
        End While
        Set i_bit to i_bit modulo by 2
        Let j_bit be j_int
        Let shift_count2 be bit_idx
        While shift_count2 is greater than 0:
            Set j_bit to j_bit divided by 2
            Set shift_count2 to shift_count2 minus 1
        End While
        Set j_bit to j_bit modulo by 2
        Let combined_pos be bit_idx multiplied by 2
        Let i_shifted be i_bit
        Let mult_i be combined_pos
        While mult_i is greater than 0:
            Set i_shifted to i_shifted multiplied by 2
            Set mult_i to mult_i minus 1
        End While
        Let j_shifted be j_bit
        Let mult_j be combined_pos plus 1
        While mult_j is greater than 0:
            Set j_shifted to j_shifted multiplied by 2
            Set mult_j to mult_j minus 1
        End While
        Set cell_index to cell_index plus i_shifted
        Set cell_index to cell_index plus j_shifted
        Set bit_idx to bit_idx plus 1
    End While
    Note: Pack: face (3 bits, high), then cell_index (2L bits)
    Let face_shifted be face
    Let face_shift_count be level multiplied by 2
    While face_shift_count is greater than 0:
        Set face_shifted to face_shifted multiplied by 2
        Set face_shift_count to face_shift_count minus 1
    End While
    Let cell_id be face_shifted plus cell_index
    Return cell_id
End Process

Process called "s2_sin_taylor" takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Local trig: 10-term Taylor with simple reduction
    Let reduced be x
    While reduced is greater than 3.141592653589793:
        Set reduced to reduced minus 6.283185307179586
    End While
    While reduced is less than 0.0 minus 3.141592653589793:
        Set reduced to reduced plus 6.283185307179586
    End While
    If reduced is greater than 1.5707963267948966:
        Set reduced to 3.141592653589793 minus reduced
    End If
    If reduced is less than 0.0 minus 1.5707963267948966:
        Set reduced to 0.0 minus 3.141592653589793 minus reduced
    End If
    Let x2 be reduced multiplied by reduced
    Let term be reduced
    Let sumv be reduced
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set sumv to sumv minus term divided by 6.0
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 120.0
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set sumv to sumv minus term divided by 5040.0
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 362880.0
    Return sumv
End Process

Process called "s2_cos_taylor" takes x as Float returns Float:
    Return s2_sin_taylor(1.5707963267948966 minus x)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - H3 cell (Uber hexagonal index, base-cell granularity)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Full H3 requires gnomonic projection of the icosahedron faces and is
Note: out of scope. We provide here the base-cell identifier (cell at level 0)
Note: which partitions the sphere into 122 cells (110 hexagonal + 12 pentagonal
Note: at the icosahedron vertices). The base-cell ID is adequate for ride-share
Note: dispatch at the continent scale and for testing infrastructure.

Process called "h3_base_cell_for_lat_lon" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Determine which of the 122 H3 base cells contains the given point.
        Uses a simplified approach: divide latitude into 11 bands of ~ 16
        degrees and longitude into 12 sectors of 30 degrees, giving 132
        cells (slightly more than the true 122 to allow for boundary
        regions). Returns a cell index in [0, 131].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        band = floor((lat + 90) / (180 / 11))
        sector = floor((lon + 180) / 30)
        cell = band * 12 + sector
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two divides, two floors, one multiply.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Note: Stack layout after stage1 prologue:
    Note:   rbp-8  = lat_degrees (param 1)
    Note:   rbp-16 = lon_degrees (param 2)
    Note:   rbp-24 = band_f
    Note:   rbp-32 = band_int
    Note:   rbp-40 = sector_f
    Note:   rbp-48 = sector_int
    Let band_f be lat_degrees plus 90.0
    Set band_f to band_f divided by 16.3636363636
    Let band_int be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-24]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-32], rax
    End Assembly
    If band_int is less than 0:
        Set band_int to 0
    End If
    If band_int is greater than 10:
        Set band_int to 10
    End If
    Let sector_f be lon_degrees plus 180.0
    Set sector_f to sector_f divided by 30.0
    Let sector_int be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-40]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-48], rax
    End Assembly
    If sector_int is less than 0:
        Set sector_int to 0
    End If
    If sector_int is greater than 11:
        Set sector_int to 11
    End If
    Let cell_idx be band_int multiplied by 12
    Set cell_idx to cell_idx plus sector_int
    Return cell_idx
End Process

Process called "h3_cell" takes lat_degrees as Float, lon_degrees as Float, resolution as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Combine the base cell with a finer-grained sub-cell index at the
        requested resolution. The H3 standard defines resolutions 0
        through 15 with each resolution dividing one parent hexagon into
        ~ 7 children (aperture 7). We approximate by using a Morton-coded
        finer grid at the resolution.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Get the base cell. Apply the resolution-multiplier factor and
        the local geohash-like grid index. Combine into a packed integer.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Inherits cost from h3_base_cell + extra log(resolution) work.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let base be h3_base_cell_for_lat_lon(lat_degrees, lon_degrees)
    Note: Build the fine index via lat/lon residues within the band/sector
    Let band_size be 16.3636363636
    Let sector_size be 30.0
    Let base_band_idx be base divided by 12
    Let base_sector_idx be base modulo by 12
    Let band_min be base_band_idx multiplied by band_size
    Set band_min to band_min minus 90.0
    Let sector_min be base_sector_idx multiplied by sector_size
    Set sector_min to sector_min minus 180.0
    Note: Convert integer band/sector indices to Float inline (avoids a dep
    Note: on arithmetic_core for this single file).
    Note: Stack layout (h3_cell):
    Note:   rbp-8   lat_degrees, rbp-16 lon_degrees, rbp-24 resolution
    Note:   rbp-32  base, rbp-40 band_size, rbp-48 sector_size
    Note:   rbp-56  base_band_idx, rbp-64 base_sector_idx
    Note:   rbp-72  band_min, rbp-80 sector_min
    Note:   rbp-88  band_min_actual, rbp-96 sector_min_actual
    Note:   rbp-104 lat_in_band, rbp-112 lon_in_sector
    Note:   rbp-120 scale_f, rbp-128 scale_i
    Note:   rbp-136 lat_frac, rbp-144 lon_frac
    Note:   rbp-152 lat_int, rbp-160 lon_int
    Let band_min_actual be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-56]
        cvtsi2sd xmm0, rax
        movq qword ptr [rbp-88], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Let sector_min_actual be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-64]
        cvtsi2sd xmm0, rax
        movq qword ptr [rbp-96], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Set band_min_actual to band_min_actual multiplied by band_size
    Set band_min_actual to band_min_actual minus 90.0
    Set sector_min_actual to sector_min_actual multiplied by sector_size
    Set sector_min_actual to sector_min_actual minus 180.0
    Let lat_in_band be lat_degrees minus band_min_actual
    Let lon_in_sector be lon_degrees minus sector_min_actual
    Note: Multiplier per resolution: aperture 7 in real H3, we use 4 here
    Let scale_f be 1.0
    Let scale_i be 0
    While scale_i is less than resolution:
        Set scale_f to scale_f multiplied by 4.0
        Set scale_i to scale_i plus 1
    End While
    Let lat_frac be lat_in_band divided by band_size
    Set lat_frac to lat_frac multiplied by scale_f
    Let lon_frac be lon_in_sector divided by sector_size
    Set lon_frac to lon_frac multiplied by scale_f
    Let lat_int be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-136]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-152], rax
    End Assembly
    Let lon_int be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-144]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-160], rax
    End Assembly
    Let scale_int be 1
    Let scale_ii be 0
    While scale_ii is less than resolution:
        Set scale_int to scale_int multiplied by 4
        Set scale_ii to scale_ii plus 1
    End While
    Let fine_index be lat_int multiplied by scale_int
    Set fine_index to fine_index plus lon_int
    Note: Pack: high bits = base (7 bits), low bits = fine_index, middle = resolution (4 bits)
    Let shift_base be base
    Let shift_base_count be (resolution multiplied by 4) plus 4
    While shift_base_count is greater than 0:
        Set shift_base to shift_base multiplied by 2
        Set shift_base_count to shift_base_count minus 1
    End While
    Let shift_res be resolution
    Let shift_res_count be resolution multiplied by 4
    While shift_res_count is greater than 0:
        Set shift_res to shift_res multiplied by 2
        Set shift_res_count to shift_res_count minus 1
    End While
    Let result be shift_base plus shift_res
    Set result to result plus fine_index
    Return result
End Process
